        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/11168",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ixti",
                        "name": "ixti",
                        "displayName": "Aleksey V. Zapparov",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "You can use _SubUserController_ but link will be like this: http:\/\/example.com\/Sub_Action\/\nor http:\/\/example.com\/Sub-Action\/\n\nAnd of course if you had to saw that Zend\/Controller\/Dispatcher.php contains not only *$unformatted = str_replace(array('-', '_', '.'), ' ', strtolower($unformatted));* in _formatName($unformatted)\n\nSo here's _formatName method from Dispatcher.php of ZendFramework 0.1.4 with my comments :)\n{code}\nprotected function _formatName($unformatted)\n{\n    \/\/ First it replaces hyphens, underscopes and dots with space of case-lowered\n    \/\/ name. So for example 'SubUser' becomes 'subuser',\n    \/\/ but 'Sub-User' becomes 'sub user'\n    $unformatted = str_replace(array('-', '_', '.'), ' ', strtolower($unformatted));\n    \/\/ Now strips all chars that are not alphanumeric or spaces, so\n    \/\/ for example 'sub& +user' becomes 'sub user'\n    $unformatted = preg_replace('[^a-z0-9 ]', '', $unformatted);\n    \/\/ returning formatted name with removed spaces and each word with\n    \/\/ capital letter, so 'sub user' becomes 'SubUser'\n    return str_replace(' ', '', ucwords($unformatted));\n}\n{code}\n\nSo it is not a bug imho.\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ixti",
                        "name": "ixti",
                        "displayName": "Aleksey V. Zapparov",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-11-07T03:36:45.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-11-07T03:36:45.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/11190",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=matthew",
                        "name": "matthew",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Weier O'Phinney",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "This is by design. URLs are case sensitive, but allowing mixed case adds complexity when propagating URLs. As a result, it was decided early that mixed case controller and action names would not be supported.\n\nThere are workarounds if you really wish to use mixed case controller\/action names, including Aleksey's solution above as well as writing your own dispatcher (this is actually pretty trivial).",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=matthew",
                        "name": "matthew",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Weier O'Phinney",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-11-07T15:47:29.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-11-07T15:47:29.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/11191",
